</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="131" type="biology_ecology">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="131">Biology.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="131">
Twenty-three individuals were collected in hilly areas in the Pedra Branca massif (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 1" captionStartId="F1" captionText="Figure 1. Distribution of new species of Amydetinae in the state of Rio de Janeiro, Brazil, in the southeastern Atlantic Forest." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.1114.77692.figure1" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/720409" pageId="0" pageNumber="131">1</figureCitation>
) at 400 m above sea level. All specimens were collected in a single, shaded humid, approximately 45° slope. Twelve specimens were collected by active search in April 2017 and eleven in April 2019. Males have a continuous green glow and often fly between 0.5 and 3 m above the ground, often in the understory, sometimes reaching up to roughly 7 m above the ground in the forest canopy. Adults are apparently active in the early twilight hours. Males lack the distinctive smell, similar to marzipan frosting, which has been reported for the type species (
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.11646/zootaxa.3640.1.6" author="Silveira, LFL" journalOrPublisher="Zootaxa" pageId="0" pageNumber="131" pagination="79 - 87" refId="B24" refString="Silveira, LFL, Mermudes, JR, 2013. Memoan ciceroi gen. et sp. n., a remarkable new firefly genus and species from the Atlantic Rainforest (Coleoptera: Lampyridae). Zootaxa 3640 (1): 79 - 87, DOI: https://doi.org/10.11646/zootaxa.3640.1.6" title="Memoan ciceroi gen. et sp. n., a remarkable new firefly genus and species from the Atlantic Rainforest (Coleoptera: Lampyridae)." url="https://doi.org/10.11646/zootaxa.3640.1.6" volume="3640" year="2013">Silveira and Mermudes 2013</bibRefCitation>
). About 2-5 males were observed flying close together in the same visual field.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="131" type="remarks">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="131">Remarks.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="131">
<taxonomicName authorityName="Campello, Vaz, Mermudes &amp; Silveira" authorityYear="2022" class="Insecta" family="Lampyridae" genus="Memoan" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Memoan conani" order="Coleoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="131" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="conani">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="131">Memoan conani</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
sp. nov. is the second species described in the genus. The differences between species are marked: labial palp (with one palpomere in 
<taxonomicName genus="Me." lsidName="Me. fruhstorferi" pageId="0" pageNumber="131" rank="species" species="fruhstorferi">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="131">Me. fruhstorferi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
comb. nov. and with two palpomeres in 
<taxonomicName genus="Me." lsidName="Me. conani" pageId="0" pageNumber="131" rank="species" species="conani">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="131">Me. conani</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
sp. nov.), which differs morphologically from the all other lampyrids as by 
<bibRefCitation author="Branham, MA" editor="Beutel, RG" journalOrPublisher="Friedrich-Schiller-Universitaet Jena, Jena" pageId="0" pageNumber="131" pagination="141 - 147" refId="B2" refString="Branham, MA, 2010. Lampyridae. In: Beutel, RG, Leschen, RAB, Eds., Handbook of Zoology IV Arthropoda: Insecta, Coleoptera: Evolution and Systematics (Polyphaga Part). Friedrich-Schiller-Universitaet Jena, Jena: 141 - 147" title="Lampyridae." volumeTitle="Handbook of Zoology IV Arthropoda: Insecta, Coleoptera: Evolution and Systematics (Polyphaga Part)." year="2010">Branham (2010)</bibRefCitation>
; scape (2 
<normalizedToken originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
longer than pedicel in 
<taxonomicName genus="Me." lsidName="Me. fruhstorferi" pageId="0" pageNumber="131" rank="species" species="fruhstorferi">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="131">Me. fruhstorferi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
comb. nov. and as long as pedicel in 
<taxonomicName genus="Me." lsidName="Me. conani" pageId="0" pageNumber="131" rank="species" species="conani">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="131">Me. conani</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
sp. nov.); antennae (serrate, with 10 antennomeres in 
<taxonomicName genus="Me." lsidName="Me. conani" pageId="0" pageNumber="131" rank="species" species="conani">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="131">Me. conani</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
sp. nov. and 
<taxonomicName genus="Me." lsidName="Me. fruhstorferi" pageId="0" pageNumber="131" rank="species" species="fruhstorferi">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="131">Me. fruhstorferi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
comb. nov., but in 
<taxonomicName genus="Me." lsidName="Me. fruhstorferi" pageId="0" pageNumber="131" rank="species" species="fruhstorferi">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="131">Me. fruhstorferi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
comb. nov. antennomeres X and XI are connate; see 
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.11646/zootaxa.3640.1.6" author="Silveira, LFL" journalOrPublisher="Zootaxa" pageId="0" pageNumber="131" pagination="79 - 87" refId="B24" refString="Silveira, LFL, Mermudes, JR, 2013. Memoan ciceroi gen. et sp. n., a remarkable new firefly genus and species from the Atlantic Rainforest (Coleoptera: Lampyridae). Zootaxa 3640 (1): 79 - 87, DOI: https://doi.org/10.11646/zootaxa.3640.1.6" title="Memoan ciceroi gen. et sp. n., a remarkable new firefly genus and species from the Atlantic Rainforest (Coleoptera: Lampyridae)." url="https://doi.org/10.11646/zootaxa.3640.1.6" volume="3640" year="2013">Silveira and Mermudes 2013</bibRefCitation>
). 
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.11646/zootaxa.3640.1.6" author="Silveira, LFL" journalOrPublisher="Zootaxa" pageId="0" pageNumber="131" pagination="79 - 87" refId="B24" refString="Silveira, LFL, Mermudes, JR, 2013. Memoan ciceroi gen. et sp. n., a remarkable new firefly genus and species from the Atlantic Rainforest (Coleoptera: Lampyridae). Zootaxa 3640 (1): 79 - 87, DOI: https://doi.org/10.11646/zootaxa.3640.1.6" title="Memoan ciceroi gen. et sp. n., a remarkable new firefly genus and species from the Atlantic Rainforest (Coleoptera: Lampyridae)." url="https://doi.org/10.11646/zootaxa.3640.1.6" volume="3640" year="2013">Silveira and Mermudes (2013)</bibRefCitation>
described the gular suture as biconcave, but, after re-examination of the material, we observed that these are actually straight throughout most of their length, but slightly divergent posteriorly in both species.
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="131">
Both species of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Silveira &amp; Mermudes" authorityYear="2013" class="Insecta" family="Lampyridae" genus="Memoan" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Memoan" order="Coleoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="131" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="131">Memoan</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
occur in remnants of montane forests, separated from one another by a distance of 400 km: 
<taxonomicName genus="Me." lsidName="Me. fruhstorferi" pageId="0" pageNumber="131" rank="species" species="fruhstorferi">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="131">Me. fruhstorferi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
comb. nov. occurs at the Santa 
<normalizedToken originalValue="Lúcia">Lucia</normalizedToken>
Biological Station, in 
<normalizedToken originalValue="Espírito">Espirito</normalizedToken>
Santo state, whereas 
<taxonomicName genus="Me." lsidName="Me. conani" pageId="0" pageNumber="131" rank="species" species="conani">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="131">Me. conani</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
sp. nov. occurs at the Massif of Pedra Branca, Rio de Janeiro state. Since fireflies are poor dispersers (
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.1080/14772000.2016.1153006" author="Silveira, LFL" journalOrPublisher="Systematics and Biodiversity" pageId="0" pageNumber="131" pagination="371 - 384" refId="B28" refString="Silveira, LFL, Khattar, G, Souto, P, Mermudes, JRM, Takiya, DM, Monteiro, RF, 2016a. Integrative taxonomy of new firefly taxa from the Atlantic Rainforest. Systematics and Biodiversity 14 (4): 371 - 384, DOI: https://doi.org/10.1080/14772000.2016.1153006" title="Integrative taxonomy of new firefly taxa from the Atlantic Rainforest." url="https://doi.org/10.1080/14772000.2016.1153006" volume="14" year="2016 a">Silveira et al. 2016a</bibRefCitation>
), we hypothesize that 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Silveira &amp; Mermudes" authorityYear="2013" class="Insecta" family="Lampyridae" genus="Memoan" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Memoan" order="Coleoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="131" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="131">Memoan</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is endemic to the Atlantic Forest biome, as it has never been found elsewhere in the field despite extensive surveys (
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.1080/00222933.2020.1749323" author="Silveira, LFL" journalOrPublisher="Journal of Natural History" pageId="0" pageNumber="131" pagination="275 - 308" refId="B31" refString="Silveira, LFL, Khattar, G, Vaz, S, Wilson, VA, Souto, PM, Mermudes, JRM, Monteiro, RF, 2020. Natural history of the fireflies of the Serra dos Orgaos mountain range (Brazil: Rio de Janeiro)-one of the 'hottest' firefly spots on Earth, with a key to genera (Coleoptera: Lampyridae). Journal of Natural History 54 (5-6): 275 - 308, DOI: https://doi.org/10.1080/00222933.2020.1749323" title="Natural history of the fireflies of the Serra dos Orgaos mountain range (Brazil: Rio de Janeiro) - one of the ' hottest' firefly spots on Earth, with a key to genera (Coleoptera: Lampyridae)." url="https://doi.org/10.1080/00222933.2020.1749323" volume="54" year="2020">Silveira et al. 2020</bibRefCitation>
) and is not present in multiple collections in Brazil (DZUP, INPA, MNRJ, MZSP) and abroad (MNHN, ZMHB). This pattern of endemicity is also seen in several other groups of fireflies (e.g., 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Hoffmannsegg in Illiger" authorityYear="1807" class="Insecta" family="Lampyridae" genus="Amydetes" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Amydetes" order="Coleoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="131" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="131">Amydetes</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
; 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Silveira, Khattar &amp; Mermudes" authorityYear="2016" class="Insecta" family="Lampyridae" genus="Luciuranus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Luciuranus" order="Coleoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="131" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="131">Luciuranus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
; 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Silveira &amp; Mermudes" authorityYear="2017" class="Insecta" family="Lampyridae" genus="Araucariocladus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Araucariocladus" order="Coleoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="131" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="131">Araucariocladus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
; and 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Campello-Goncalves, Souto, Mermudes &amp; Silveira" authorityYear="2019" class="Insecta" family="Lampyridae" genus="Uanauna" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Uanauna" order="Coleoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="131" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="131">Uanauna</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="131">
<taxonomicName authorityName="Campello, Vaz, Mermudes &amp; Silveira" authorityYear="2022" class="Insecta" family="Lampyridae" genus="Memoan" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Memoan conani" order="Coleoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="131" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="conani">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="131">Memoan conani</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
sp. nov. were only seen in a narrow spatial and temporal window; that is, males were only observed and collected in a single slope within the limits of the PEPB at an altitude around 400 m a.s.l., and only in April. Likewise, 
<taxonomicName genus="Me." lsidName="Me. fruhstorferi" pageId="0" pageNumber="131" rank="species" species="fruhstorferi">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="131">Me. fruhstorferi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
comb. nov. has only been collected at about 600 m a.s.l., also exclusively in April. Such narrow environmental preferences have been reported for most firefly species occurring in the Atlantic Forest (
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.1080/00222933.2020.1749323" author="Silveira, LFL" journalOrPublisher="Journal of Natural History" pageId="0" pageNumber="131" pagination="275 - 308" refId="B31" refString="Silveira, LFL, Khattar, G, Vaz, S, Wilson, VA, Souto, PM, Mermudes, JRM, Monteiro, RF, 2020. Natural history of the fireflies of the Serra dos Orgaos mountain range (Brazil: Rio de Janeiro)-one of the 'hottest' firefly spots on Earth, with a key to genera (Coleoptera: Lampyridae). Journal of Natural History 54 (5-6): 275 - 308, DOI: https://doi.org/10.1080/00222933.2020.1749323" title="Natural history of the fireflies of the Serra dos Orgaos mountain range (Brazil: Rio de Janeiro) - one of the ' hottest' firefly spots on Earth, with a key to genera (Coleoptera: Lampyridae)." url="https://doi.org/10.1080/00222933.2020.1749323" volume="54" year="2020">Silveira et al. 2020</bibRefCitation>
). Given the narrow geographic range, both 
<taxonomicName genus="Me." lsidName="Me. conani" pageId="0" pageNumber="131" rank="species" species="conani">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="131">Me. conani</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
sp. nov. and 
<taxonomicName genus="Me." lsidName="Me. fruhstorferi" pageId="0" pageNumber="131" rank="species" species="fruhstorferi">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="131">Me. fruhstorferi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
comb. nov. may be seriously threatened by habitat loss, like many other Atlantic Forest endemics.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
